INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`,`post_author`,`post_date`,`post_date_gmt`,`post_content`,`post_title`,`post_excerpt`,`post_status`,`comment_status`,`ping_status`,`post_password`,`post_name`,`to_ping`,`pinged`,`post_modified`,`post_modified_gmt`,`post_content_filtered`,`post_parent`,`guid`,`menu_order`,`post_type`,`post_mime_type`,`comment_count`) VALUES ('247','3','2013-06-05 20:26:52','2013-06-05 20:26:52','<p><a href=\"http://blog.asolutions.com/\">Blog.asolutions.com</a>Â /Â <a href=\"http://blog.asolutions.com/wp-admin\">Sign in</a>Â (user name/password is not the same as network account)</p><p>Also see thread inÂ <a href=\"https://intranet.asolutions.com/node/193\">Blogging forum</a>.</p><p>Below are general strategies, tips, ideas on writing blog content. As you get started, please review these notes to help you acquire a better understanding of the process.</p><h2>I. GENERAL TIPS</h2><p>1. Slow Down. Take your time like you would for a proposal or business letter. Donât be in a rush to create content and publish it. Craft your post and let it sit for awhile (maybe a day) and review it for flow, punctuation, style, professionalism.</p><p>2. Premise. Where to start? You start your post with a good ideaâ¦premise, angle, theme.Â  Start with the focus of your story and go from there.</p><p>2A. Keep an idea folder filled with ideas for future posts.</p><p>2B. Use mind mapping techniques that allow you to start with a thought and off of that idea think of other ideas that come to mindâ¦ you will acquire an excellent, focused premise for a post.</p><p>2C. Donât focus on yourself but rather your blog readers. What would they like to read aboutâ¦put yourself in their shoes. One key thought is to focus on a need or problem area and help solve that for the reader by sharing information.</p><p>2D. One topic per postâ¦donât try to address more than one issue in any given post.</p><p>2E. Make it current and relevant.</p><p>Â </p><h2>II. THE TITLE</h2><p>The most important words in your post are your title. Each word should be powerful and move the reader. Readers will review the title and give it a âyeahâ or ânayâ on moving forward.</p><p>Â âThe purpose of your title is to get potential readers to read the first line of your content,â David Ogilvy, Advertising Expert.</p><p>Blog post titles appear in:</p><p>Â Â  Â â¢Â Â  Â Search engine results</p><p>Â Â  Â â¢Â Â  Â RSS feeds</p><p>Â Â  Â â¢Â Â  Â Links from other bloggers</p><p>Â Â  Â â¢Â Â  Â Social media sites</p><p>Â Â  Â â¢Â Â  Â On your archive page</p><p>Tips on titles:</p><p>1. Donât rushâthink it through.</p><p>2. Communicate a benefit, solve a problem, address a need: A successful example: â10 Ways to Take Stunning Portraitsâ</p><p>3. Create Controversy or Debate</p><p>4. Ask a Question (directed at readers-not just a blank question)</p><p>5. Personalize Titles for Readers (by using the word âYouâ)</p><p>6. Keep it Short. This is good for readers both also search enginesâ¦try to keep under 65 characters and donât use periods in title.</p><p>7. Keywords.Â  Keywords grab readersâ attention and help with long tail life of post as search engines rank them higher. Keywords at the start of the title have more impact with SEO.</p><p>8. Use Power Words. For example, âFree.â Be careful though as big words (such as stunning, discover, secrets) can sound like hyperbole. Free advice might by considered hype while âFree e-Bookâ could be considered a benefit and attraction for pulling in readers.</p><p>9. Make Big Claims (and back them up).</p><p>10. Use Humor (but only if you are 100% that it is funny).</p><p>Â </p><h2>III. THE OPENING LINE</h2><p>While the title is the most important part of the post, the lead is the second most important. Here are strategies for writing the opening line.</p><p>1. Identify a Needâ¦ augment what was said in title.</p><p>2. Ask a Question with Only One Answer. For example, âDo you want to discover how to convince your client that Agile should be used for their project?â</p><p>3. Ask an Intriguing Questionâ¦âShould Agile be used for military IT projects?â</p><p>4. Say Something out of the Ordinary or Controversialâ¦a grabber.</p><p>5. Tell a Story or Share an Analogy. For example, âWhile working for the U.S. Army, we learned 5 reasons why military projects are successful.â</p><p>6. Make a Claim or Promise. âIn this post, you will learn the secrets in coming under budget in your next software development project.â</p><p>7. Paint a Pictureâ¦âYour projects are always over budget or exceed deadlines, which causes tension between you and your client. We used to have the same problem, butâ¦</p><p>8. Use Startling Statistics.</p><p>9. Start with a Quote</p><p>10. Use an Image</p><h2>Â </h2><h2>IV. STAY ON MESSAGE</h2><p>1. Identify a goal statement to achieve by publishing the postâstart with a âI am going to teach, inform, educate, entertain, inspire, share with my readers on HOW TO â¦.Reflect back to this goal statement during the writing and after to make sure your post is on track and on message.</p><p>Remember:</p><ul><li>One point per post.</li><li>Who are your readers?</li><li>WIFT (whatâs in it for them)â¦does it pass the âso whatâ or âwho caresâ test? Whatâs the benefit for the reader to read this post?</li><li>Multiple thoughts? Then write multiple posts.</li></ul><p>Â </p><h2>V. THE VOICE</h2><p>Your blog should sound like âyou.â Donât try to reinvent yourself for the blog. Just be yourself and write as though you are writing to a friend but your mission is a bit different. Also of significant importanceâ¦remember your role in all this. You are trying to inform, educate, shareâ¦not sell. If you remember that key point you will be fine.</p><p>Read other blogs to get a good feel for the type of voice expectedâ¦here is one example.</p><p>âPR + CUSTOMER SERVICE MERGER ACCELERATINGâ</p><p>âAbout a year ago, I posted the graphic about âThe Next 50 Years of Public Relations. At that point, my focus was primarily on the waning emphasis on âMedia Relations.â In the intervening months, as predicted, our role as âPR Counselorsâ has evolved even more quickly than I suspected last June.â</p><p>Â </p><h2>VI. TWO WAY COMMUNICATION</h2><p>1. Call to Action (CTA)â¦Invite readers to comment, subscribe, vote, share feedback, point to Twitter, RSS feed, or newsletter etc.</p><p>2. Know what you want readers to do from reading post (e.g. learn) and ask them for a pertinent call to action</p><p>3.Â  One CTA per post</p><p>4. Make the CTA a win/win for you and reader</p><p>5.Â  Make CTA simple and easy to do and easy to understand what to do</p><p>6. Put CTAs in posts first, then sidebars second</p><p>7.Â  Okay to insert CTA at beginning and end of post-beginning sets the stage</p><p>8.Â  Use formatting to make CTA stand out</p><p>9. Explain why CTA would benefit others in the community</p><p>10. At times, add an incentive for CTA (free white paper, free e-book)</p><p>11. Vary CTAs from posts to posts</p><p>12. CTA is not a hard sell but related to blog and its mission</p><p>Â </p><h2>VII. ADDING DEPTH</h2><p>1. Share real world examples not theory; use analogies and metaphors</p><p>2.Â  Inject your expertise and opinion</p><p>3. Point reader to further reading (either with hyperlinks inside the post or at end of posts with a recommended reading list)â¦you can include your white paper or other research material as well</p><p>4. Use quotes related to your topic (customers, analysts, universities, authors, associations, thought leaders)</p><p>5. Interview someoneâconsider adding in a video interview</p><p>6. Use comments from previous published posts and share into new posts. This adds voice to your posts and shows that you are engaged.Â </p><p>6A. Ask readers a few days before your posts to post their questions or comments about the topic and then include in upcoming post</p><p>7. Do a âcall for commentsâ on social messaging sites and get comment (Twitter, Plurk, LinkedIn, email readers directly, etc.</p><p>8. Give homework to your readers and include information in future post</p><p>9. More interactivityâ¦add a poll, invite readers to guest blog or blog about this topic in their blog</p><p>10. Add high-end graphics, illustrations, photography, 3d imagery that are related and provide true value</p><p>11. Present both sides of a story and ask for reader feedback on your analysis in your postÂ </p><p>12. Do a part one and part two series and invite readers to come back</p><p>Â </p><h2>VIII. EDITING</h2><ol><li>Â Â  Spend significant time editing before hitting publishÂ Read out loud to someone</li><li>Â Â  Print and read hard copy (not just on monitor)</li><li>Â Â  Take time after writing (perhaps one day), let it sit, then edit it</li><li>Â Â Â  Have a second set of eyes read it</li><li>Â Â Â  Read it for different perspectives (punctuation, grammar, content, message, flow, transitions, etc.)</li><li>Â Â Â  Test all links to ensure quality</li><li>Â Â Â  Use spell check</li><li>Â Â Â  Letâs standardizeâ¦AP Standards:Â Â Â <a title=\"http://www.apstylebook.com/?do=product&amp;pid=OLN-917360\" href=\"http://www.apstylebook.com/?do=product&amp;pid=OLN-917360\">http://www.apstylebook.com/?do=product&amp;pid=OLN-917360</a></li><li>Â Â Â  Check this blog out for help as well:Â Â <a title=\"http://data.grammarbook.com/blog/\" href=\"http://data.grammarbook.com/blog/\">http://data.grammarbook.com/blog/</a></li></ol><p>Â </p><h2>IX. POLISHING YOUR BLOG</h2><p>1. Images---some times multiple ones. A good picture or good formatting can grab attention in RSS feeds</p><p>1A. Use of video, charts, graphs, tablesâvisuals connect stronger than text</p><p>2. Formattingâsub headings, captions, bullets, bolding, italics, font size, quote</p><p>3. Step back and look at first visual impression of post</p><p>4. Make it easy to scanâeasy to read, bullets, subheads</p><p>5. White spaceâbreak paragraphs into small, readable pieces</p><p>6. Keep posts shortâtoo long, if too long write multiple posts\\</p><p>Â </p><h2>X. GOOD CONTENT</h2><ol><li>Usefulness and Uniqueness -Â  Your blog needs to be useful and unique to your readers--Start with the customer â find out what they need and want and give it to them.</li><li>Education â some readers are primarily interested in learning something about a given topic.â¨</li><li>Information â many blogs are built on the thirst that some have to be informed on an issue, product or topicâ¨</li><li>Debate â some blog readers want a place that they can have a good old fashioned dialogue, debate or even a fight over an issue</li><li>News â many blog readers just want to be kept up to date in a fieldâ¨</li><li>Community â Iâm aware of some very successful blogs that tap into the need that people have to connect and belong. Quite often the topic is secondary to these connections.</li><li>Research your Readership--Research your readership or potential readership. Ask for feedback.Â  Survey colleagues. Look at other peopleâs blogs on a topic (especially their comments section to see what types of questions people are asking) and look in forums and discussion groups on topics where there is usually a lot of question asking going on.</li><li>Distinguish yourself--Surf other blogs in your niche and analyze the content. In most niches, sites present very similar information in pretty much the same voice, tone and style. As a new blogger you can either replicate what they are doing and try to do it better (difficult as they will already have loyal readers and unless youâre brilliant at it youâre unlikely to convert these readers over to you) OR you can distinguish yourself in some way from what others are doing.</li><li>This might mean tackling a slightly different topic perhaps a sub niche but also mean writing in a distinct voice. It might also mean writing in a different genre of posts (i.e. if everyone else is writing ânewsyâ posts you might like to write more âopinionâ type posts). Bring together the elements of both Useful and Unique content and you will be one step closer to a successful blog.</li><li>Original Content â Shoot for publishing your original content in your own words. However, clever and fair use of other peopleâs content (always giving credit for it and using it within a âfair useâ way â i.e. only using short quotesâ) CAN be worth doing IF you use it in a way that is useful to your readers.</li></ol>','Asynchrony\'s Blog Program Guide','','publish','open','open','','asynchronys-blog-program-guide','','','2013-06-05 20:26:52','2013-06-05 20:26:52','','0','https://intra-dev.asynchrony.com/help-article/asynchronys-blog-program-guide/','0','help-article','','0');
