INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`,`post_author`,`post_date`,`post_date_gmt`,`post_content`,`post_title`,`post_excerpt`,`post_status`,`comment_status`,`ping_status`,`post_password`,`post_name`,`to_ping`,`pinged`,`post_modified`,`post_modified_gmt`,`post_content_filtered`,`post_parent`,`guid`,`menu_order`,`post_type`,`post_mime_type`,`comment_count`) VALUES ('358','6','2013-06-12 21:49:35','2013-06-12 21:49:35','<img src=\"https://intra-dev.asynchrony.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/founders.png\" width=\"602\" height=\"232\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-491\" />\n\n<h2>Overview</h2>\nAsynchrony is one of the leading Agile development shops and training organizations in the Midwest. Our Agile development practices have been independently appraised at CMMI Level 3, indicating the maturity of the processes we use that underlie our Agile development projects. The company employs nationally known Agile thought leaders that are frequently published and/or quoted in the media with respect to Agile. Examples of Asynchrony\'s contributions to the global discussions about Agile can be found atÂ <a href=\"http://www.asynchrony.com/category/news/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.asynchrony.com/category/news/</a>. An executive of Schafer and former CIO of the Air Force and the Department of Energy, John Gilligan, is a frequent speaker and author with respect to Agile adoption within the DoD and has served on numerous committees tasked with advising on national policy changes with respect to IT system development and portfolio management.\n\nIn addition to being recognized as a leading Agile development shop, Asynchrony is also widely known for our Agile training, mentoring and coaching practice. Asynchrony has trained thousands of people and the company has developed a wide array of courses that it offers both publicly and privately. Asynchrony has created the courses and teaches all the Agile classes offered by Washington University\'s CAIT (Center for the Application of Information Technology). We have also successfully supported Agile transformation projects within very large global organizations.\n<h2>Dot Com Days</h2>\nAsynchrony was founded in 1999 by brothers Bob, Steve, and Dave Elfanbaum and their friend Nate McKie. The group wanted to dramatically change the paradigm of global software development by combining the social networking and collaborative dynamics of the open source development community with an innovative business model and enabling technologies. Asynchrony was born as a Web 2.0 company (in 1999) focused on global collaboration.\n\nThe early days were exciting as the founders built a global community of designers, developers, project managers and testers with more than 35,000 members from over 160 countries working on 1,500 separate software projects. The site was running 24*7 and meeting all expectations; they were well on their way to success.\n\nAsynchronyâs management team simultaneously created a consulting counterpart, Asynchrony Solutions, to provide additional capital for the growing .com site. Asynchrony Solutions provided consulting and development services to corporate customers. Steve and Nate âgrew upâ at GE, Bob at Price Waterhouse; they understood both the benefits and challenges of working with consulting organizations. They brought that experience to Asynchrony Solutionsâ first customers, which included Fleet Mortgage, Time Warner and GE Capital.\n\nIn late 2001, the dot.com bubble burst. Asynchrony.com, just 2 years old, faced its first crisis. What were Bob, Steve, Dave, and Nate going to do now?\n\n<img src=\"https://intra-dev.asynchrony.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/breaking-ground.png\" alt=\"\" title=\"\"width=\"602\" height=\"232\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-492\" /></a>\n\n<h2>Moving Forward</h2>\nAsynchrony Solutions - The first thing the founders decided was that they were not going to give up and return to their traditional corporate jobs. The consulting side of the company was thriving, so they developed a plan to turn their virtual dot.com collaboration site into a brick and mortar project-based software capability, and use the platform as a strategic differentiator in the consulting market.\n\nPerhaps the most important decision they made was that they were not going to conduct business like a traditional consulting company. They had seen so many cases of consultants wasting too much time generating requirements documents and making recommendations and leaving without anything to show except a pile of paper and a big hole in the companyâs budget. The Asynchrony team was determined to generate workable software â they were going to focus on solutions, not piles of paper. The problem to solve was how to create quality software that consistently exceeded the clientsâ expectations within time and budget expectations.\n\nThe solution they found was <a href=\"http://asynchrony.com/aboutus-methodology.html\">Agile</a>, a relatively new approach being promoted at the time that featured, amongst other things, frequent iterations of capability development and frequent customer involvement.\n\nThe premise: itâs in the customerâs best interest to fail faster, adjust, and then get it right, and do this in small increments of a week or two at most. Their previous experience taught them that customer requirements are never fully known at the beginning, so using Agile was an excellent alternative to traditional life cycle development methods. History has proven the Asynchrony founders right. The companyâs development projects have always met or exceeded customer requirements. Furthermore, Agile methods are now catching on at numerous software development companies, large and small, as the best way to develop software.\n\nOver the last decade, Asynchrony has helped some of the largest organizations in the world deliver software, improve their architecture, and train, mentor and coach their teams.\n\nIn 2010, Asynchrony was acquired by Schafer Corporation. Schafer is a scientific and engineering company providing technical solutions to mission critical challenges in national security.Â Â  This acquisition gives Asynchrony access to additional capital to help it more rapidly grow its business and invest in key enabling technologies.','Company','','inherit','open','open','','20-autosave','','','2013-06-12 21:49:35','2013-06-12 21:49:35','','20','https://intra-dev.asynchrony.com/20-autosave/','0','revision','','0');
